    "caption": "The tiny musician who sings with its wings.",
    "shortDescription": "Male crickets make their chirping song by scraping one wing against the other — there's a row of ridges on one wing and a scraper on the other, working like a tiny bow and string. They chirp to attract females, and females actually choose the ones they like best. Fun fact: You can roughly estimate the temperature outside by counting cricket chirps — the warmer it is, the faster they chirp."
